<DOC><DOCNO> AP891114-0244 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1345EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     11-14 0395</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0408</SECOND><HEAD>Downward Trend for Big Three Continues</HEAD><HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD><BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of the nation's Big Three automakers' NorthAmerican-built cars and light trucks continued a downward spiral inearly November, falling 22.4 percent from last year, the companiesreported Tuesday.   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. saidthey sold an average of 24,094 vehicles a day from Nov. 1-10 thisyear, compared with 31,038 a day during the same time last year.   Car sales were off 26.2 percent and truck sales were down 16.2percent for the Big Three.   The sales continued a trend begun in the first 10-day reportingperiod of October, as the 1990 model year opened.   Analysts had forecast slumping car and truck sales during thefourth quarter of this year because carbuyers headed to theshowrooms weeks before to avoid 1990-model price increases and totake advantage of incentive programs on 1989 models.   Those programs have been whittled for 1990 vehicles.   In October, car and light truck sales by the Big Three were down14.1 percent from the year before. That slump pushed October'sretail sales down 1 percent, the first decline in eight months.   The early-November sales pace of 24,094 vehicles a day was 17percent below the 29,016 vehicle-a-day sales pace during the sameperiod a month ago.   So far this year, car and truck sales by the Big Three wererunning 4.3 percent behind last year's pace. Car sales were down6.2 percent and truck sales were off 1.1 percent.   In early November, GM posted the largest decline in car sales,dropping 29.1 percent from the year-ago period. Light truck salesreported by GM were 20.9 percent below last year's pace. For theyear, GM's car sales were off 7.3 percent while truck sales were upa slim 0.3 percent.   Ford's early-November car sales were down 23.5 percent and trucksales were off 14.3 percent compared with last year. Year-to-datecar sales at Ford were down 1.6 percent and truck sales wererunning 3.2 percent behind the year-to-date pace last year.   Sales of Chrysler's cars were down 22.5 percent for the period,and light truck sales were down 9.9 percent. Car sales this yearwere running 11.6 percent behind last year's pace and truck saleswere down 0.6 percent.</TEXT></DOC>